Answer: $b_{1}=3, q=\frac{1}{2}$.

Solution. It is known that the sum of the first $n$ terms of a geometric progression with the first term $b_{1}$ and common ratio $q$ is $\frac{b_{1}\left(1-q^{n}\right)}{1-q}$. For a decreasing infinite geometric progression, $|q|<1$, so as $n$ approaches infinity, $q^{n}$ approaches zero, and the sum of the terms approaches $\frac{b_{1}}{1-q}$.

All terms of the given progression $\left\{b_{n}\right\}$ with odd indices also form a geometric progression with the first term $b_{1}$ and common ratio $q^{2}$, and all terms with even indices form a geometric progression with the first term $b_{2}=b_{1} q$ and common ratio $q^{2}$. The sums of these terms are $\frac{b_{1}}{1-q^{2}}$ and $\frac{b_{1} q}{1-q^{2}}$, respectively.

The squares of the terms of the progression at odd and even positions also form geometric progressions with the first term $b_{1}^{2}$ and common ratio $q^{2}$, and with the first term $b_{2}^{2}=b_{1}^{2} q^{2}$ and common ratio $q^{4}$, respectively. Their sums are $\frac{b_{1}^{2}}{1-q^{4}}$ and $\frac{b_{1}^{2} q^{2}}{1-q^{4}}$. From the condition, we obtain the system of equations

$$
\left\{\begin{array} { l } 
{ \frac { b _ { 1 } } { 1 - q ^ { 2 } } - \frac { b _ { 1 } q } { 1 - q ^ { 2 } } = 2 , } \\
{ \frac { b _ { 1 } ^ { 2 } } { 1 - q ^ { 4 } } - \frac { b _ { 1 } ^ { 2 } q ^ { 2 } } { 1 - q ^ { 4 } } = \frac { 3 6 } { 5 } }
\end{array} \Leftrightarrow \left\{\begin{array} { l } 
{ \frac { b _ { 1 } ( 1 - q ) } { ( 1 - q ) ( 1 + q ) } = 2 } \\
{ \frac { b _ { 1 } ^ { 2 } ( 1 - q ^ { 2 } ) } { ( 1 - q ^ { 2 } ) ( 1 + q ^ { 2 } ) } = \frac { 3 6 } { 5 } }
\end{array} \Leftrightarrow \left\{\begin{array}{l}
\frac{b_{1}}{1+q}=2 \\
\frac{b_{1}^{2}}{1+q^{2}}=\frac{36}{5}
\end{array}\right.\right.\right.
$$

We square both sides of the first equation and then divide the second equation by the first term-by-term. We get $\frac{1+2 q+q^{2}}{1+q^{2}}=\frac{9}{5} \Leftrightarrow 4 q^{2}-10 q+4=0$, from which $q=2$ or $q=\frac{1}{2}$. Since the progression is decreasing and infinite, $|q|<1$, and only the value $q=\frac{1}{2}$ is valid. Then $b_{1}=2(1+q)=3$.

