## Problem Kuznetsov Differentiation 19-2

$$
\begin{gathered}
S=\left[1+\frac{1}{p-1}\right]+\left[\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{p-2}\right)+\left[\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{p-3}\right)+\ldots+\left(\frac{1}{\frac{1}{2}(p-1)}+\frac{1}{\frac{1}{2}(p+1)}\right)= \\
=\frac{p}{p-1}+\frac{p}{2 \cdot(p-2)}+\frac{p}{3 \cdot(p-3)}+\ldots+\frac{p}{\frac{1}{2}\left(p^{2}-1\right)}
\end{gathered}
$$

The number of addends in the sum is $p-1$. Since $p$ is a prime number greater than 2, $p$ is odd, and thus $p-1$ is even.

We can write the sum $S$ in the following form:

$$
\begin{gathered}
S=\left[1+\frac{1}{p-1}\right]+\left[\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{p-2}\right)+\left[\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{p-3}\right)+\ldots+\left(\frac{1}{\frac{1}{2}(p-1)}+\frac{1}{\frac{1}{2}(p+1)}\right)= \\
=\frac{p}{p-1}+\frac{p}{2 \cdot(p-2)}+\frac{p}{3 \cdot(p-3)}+\ldots+\frac{p}{\frac{1}{2}\left(p^{2}-1\right)}
\end{gathered}
$$

After adding these fractions, we get a fraction whose numerator is divisible by $p$, and whose denominator is the product

$$
1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot \ldots \cdot(p-1)=(p-1)!
$$

which is coprime with $p$. Therefore, the number $p$ in the numerator of this last fraction cannot be canceled out.

